            <section class="prose mt-6">
              <h2>How this stairs calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool designs a straight run of stairs from your
                floor-to-floor height and optional available run. It follows the
                same logic a carpenter uses on site, but does the math instantly
                and checks comfort and typical building code ranges.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Choose units and enter total rise</h3>
              <p>
                Start by selecting <strong>Imperial (ft / in)</strong> or
                <strong>Metric (mm)</strong>. Then enter the
                <strong>total rise</strong> – the vertical distance from the
                finished lower floor to the finished upper floor.
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <strong>Number of risers</strong><br />
                \( n_r =
                \text{round}\left(\dfrac{H_\text{total}}{h_\text{target}}\right)
                \)<br />
                \( h_\text{actual} = \dfrac{H_\text{total}}{n_r} \)
              </div>

              <p>
                If you leave the target riser height blank, the calculator uses
                a typical comfortable value (about 7&nbsp;in / 180&nbsp;mm) and
                then adjusts to make all risers equal.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Treads, run and stringer length</h3>
              <p>For a straight stair:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Number of treads</strong> = number of risers − 1
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Total horizontal run</strong> = treads × tread run
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Stringer length</strong> is the hypotenuse of a right
                  triangle formed by total rise and total run.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <strong>Stair geometry</strong><br />
                \( n_t = n_r - 1 \)<br />
                \( R_\text{total} = n_t \times d \)<br />
                \( L_\text{stringer} = \sqrt{H_\text{total}^2 +
                R_\text{total}^2} \)<br />
                where \(d\) is tread run (depth).
              </div>

              <p>
                If you specify an <strong>available horizontal run</strong>, the
                calculator adjusts the tread depth to fit that space while
                staying as close as possible to your target run and comfort
                rules.
              </p>

              <h3>3. Comfort rules and code checks</h3>
              <p>
                Most stair codes and ergonomic guidelines aim for stairs that
                are neither too steep nor too shallow. This calculator checks:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Riser height</strong> – typically ≤ 7.75&nbsp;in
                  (197&nbsp;mm) for residential stairs.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Tread depth</strong> – typically ≥ 10&nbsp;in
                  (254&nbsp;mm) measured horizontally.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>2 × rise + run rule</strong> – a comfort rule of
                  thumb:
                  <span class="whitespace-nowrap"
                    >\( 24\text{–}25\text{ in} \) (610–635&nbsp;mm).</span
                  >
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Headroom</strong> – approximate check against a
                  typical minimum of 80&nbsp;in (2032&nbsp;mm).
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The colored dots in the results panel show whether each item is
                within these ranges (green), borderline (amber), or outside
                (red). These are guidance values only; always confirm with your
                local building code.
              </p>

              <h3>4. Estimating number of stringers</h3>
              <p>
                The number of stringers depends on stair width, tread material
                and load. This calculator uses a simple rule of thumb:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Up to ~36&nbsp;in (915&nbsp;mm) wide:
                  <strong>2 stringers</strong>
                </li>
                <li>
                  36–48&nbsp;in (915–1220&nbsp;mm): <strong>3 stringers</strong>
                </li>
                <li>
                  48–60&nbsp;in (1220–1525&nbsp;mm):
                  <strong>4 stringers</strong>
                </li>
                <li>
                  Wider stairs: consider 5+ stringers or engineered design
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                For composite decking or thinner treads, you may need more
                stringers than these minimums.
              </p>

              <h2>Step‑by‑step: laying out a stair stringer</h2>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Use this calculator to get <strong>riser height</strong>,
                  <strong>tread run</strong>, and
                  <strong>number of treads</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Set a framing square with those rise and run values using
                  stair gauges or clamps.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Starting from the top of the stringer, mark each step position
                  along the board.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Adjust the <strong>bottom cut</strong> to account for tread
                  thickness (the bottom riser is usually shorter by the tread
                  thickness).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Cut the first stringer carefully and use it as a template for
                  the others.
                </li>
              </ol>
              <p>
                Always dry‑fit the stringers and treads before final fastening,
                and confirm that all risers are within the maximum variation
                allowed by your local code.
              </p>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>What is the ideal stair angle?</h3>
              <p>
                Comfortable residential stairs usually fall between
                <strong>30° and 37°</strong> from horizontal. Steeper than about
                40° feels like a ladder; shallower than 25° feels like a ramp.
                The calculator shows the exact angle based on your rise and run.
              </p>

              <h3>Do I enter finished or rough dimensions?</h3>
              <p>
                Enter <strong>finished</strong> floor‑to‑floor height and, if
                possible, finished tread depth. If you only know rough framing
                dimensions, remember to subtract floor and tread finishes when
                laying out your stringers.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I use this for building code approval?</h3>
              <p>
                No. This calculator is an educational and planning aid. It uses
                common residential code ranges, but it does not replace a
                stamped design or local code review. Always check your final
                design with your building department or a qualified
                professional.
              </p>
            </section>
